## 5. End-to-End Flow (How It All Connects)

### Step 1 — Data Generation
```
data_generator.py  →  data/data_file.csv
```
Simulates 1092 traces of ransomware + benign activity with realistic HPC & I/O patterns.

### Step 2 — Model Training
```
ml_models.py reads data_file.csv
    → Trains 5 classifiers × 3 modes = 15 models
    → Evaluates each with balanced accuracy, F1, etc.
    → Saves best model to models/best_model.pkl
    → Saves results to models/all_results.json + model_info.json
```

### Step 3 — Launch Dashboard
```
python app.py  →  Flask server starts on http://127.0.0.1:5000
    → Loads best_model.pkl into SystemMonitor
    → Serves web pages + API endpoints
```

### Step 4 — Live Detection
```
User opens /monitoring page
    → monitoring.js polls /api/detect every few seconds
    → monitor.py collects live CPU & disk data via psutil
    → Computes 52 statistical features
    → Feeds features into the trained model
    → Returns prediction: ransomware (1) or benign (0)
    → Dashboard shows real-time alerts
```

---

## 6. Key Results (From Training)

The best model is **Random Forest on Integrated (HPC + I/O) data**:

| Metric | Score |
|---|---|
| Balanced Accuracy | **1.0** |
| F1-Score | **1.0** |
| Precision | **1.0** |
| Recall | **1.0** |
| FPR | **0.0** |
| ROC-AUC | **1.0** |

All 5 classifiers achieve near-perfect scores. Decision Tree has the lowest with 0.9999 balanced accuracy (2 FP, 1 FN out of ~93,600 samples).

---

## 7. Common Review Questions & Answers

**Q: Why use HPC events instead of file signatures?**
> HPCs capture low-level CPU behaviour (cache misses, branch misses) that ransomware can't easily hide. Signature-based methods miss zero-day or obfuscated ransomware.

**Q: What are the 3 detection modes?**
> **HPC-only** (20 features from CPU events), **I/O-only** (32 features from disk events), and **Integrated** (52 features combining both). Integrated is the most accurate.

**Q: Why these 5 HPC events specifically?**
> The paper tested many HPCs and found these 5 have the highest discriminative power between ransomware and benign apps, even under heavy workloads.

**Q: How is the data collected?**
> In the paper: via `perf stat` (HPC) and `virsh domblkstat` (I/O) on KVM VMs. In our implementation: simulated with realistic patterns, and live monitoring uses `psutil`.

**Q: What is the 200 ms instance window?**
> Each "instance" is a 200 ms time window. Within it, 40 HPC samples (every 5 ms) and 10 I/O samples (every 20 ms) are collected, then summarised into 4 statistical features each.

**Q: Why Random Forest as the best model?**
> It achieved perfect scores on the integrated dataset with no false positives or false negatives. Its ensemble of decision trees handles the feature space well.

**Q: What workload types are tested?**
> 6 types: Base Load (idle), CPU-intensive (10+ apps), and Network-intensive (30+ apps). This ensures detection works even when the system is under heavy legitimate load.

**Q: How many ransomware families are covered?**
> 10: Sodinokibi, Netwalker, Ryuk, Conti, LockBit, DarkSide, BlackMatter, REvil, Maze, WannaCry.

**Q: What is the train/test split?**
> 70% training, 30% testing, with `random_state=42` for reproducibility.

**Q: What does the scaler do?**
> `StandardScaler` normalises features to zero mean and unit variance, which is critical for SVM and kNN to work correctly (they're distance-sensitive).

